SIMPLE: obey
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Obey
<hw>O*bey"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Obeyed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Obeying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>obeyen</ets>, F.
<ets>ob⟦eacute⟧ir</ets>, fr. L. <ets>obedire</ets>, <ets>oboedire</ets>;
<ets>ob</ets> (see Ob-) + <ets>audire</ets> to hear. See
<er>Audible</er>, and cf. <er>Obeisance</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
give ear to; to execute the commands of; to yield submission to; to
comply with the orders of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Children, <qex>obey</qex> your parents in the Lord.</q>
<rj><qau>Eph. vi. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Was she the God, that her thou didst <qex>obey</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To submit to the authority of; to be ruled
by.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My will <qex>obeyed</qex> his will.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Afric and India shall his power <qex>obey</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To yield to the impulse, power, or operation of;
<as>as, a ship <ex>obeys</ex> her helm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obey</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Obey
<hw>O*bey"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To give obedience.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Will he <qex>obey</qex> when one commands?</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ By some old writers <xex>obey</xex> was used, as in the
French idiom, with the preposition <xex>to</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His servants ye are, <qex>to</qex> whom ye <qex>obey</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Rom. vi. 16.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He commanded the trumpets to sound: <qex>to</qex> which the two
brave knights <qex>obeying</qex>, they performed their courses.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir. P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Obeyer</ent>⟦br⟧
